attack_pattern.title: Initial Access
attack_pattern.description: Adversaries use techniques to gain entry into a victim's environment. This stage marks the beginning of the intrusion campaign and is often achieved through exploiting vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, or weaknesses in systems or networks. Adversaries may also leverage social engineering tactics, such as phishing emails or malicious links, to trick users into providing credentials or downloading malicious files.

techniques.title: Exploit Public-Facing Application
techniques.description: Adversaries exploit vulnerabilities in publicly accessible applications, such as web servers, web applications, or other internet-facing services, to gain unauthorized access to a victim's environment. Public-facing applications are often targeted by adversaries due to their accessibility from the internet, making them potential entry points for intrusion.

attack_pattern.title: Execution
attack_pattern.description: Adversaries use techniques to run malicious code or commands on a target system or environment. This tactic covers various methods adversaries employ to execute their malicious payloads, such as files, scripts, or commands, to achieve their objectives within the target environment. Execution techniques may include exploiting vulnerabilities, abusing legitimate system utilities, or tricking users into executing malicious files or scripts.

techniques.title: Command and Scripting Interpreter
techniques.description: Adversaries use command-line interfaces (CLI) or scripting languages to execute commands, scripts, or malicious code on a target system. These techniques allow adversaries to interact with the operating system, run tools, manipulate files, and perform various actions to achieve their objectives within the target environment.

course_of_action.remediation:
Keep all software, including operating systems, applications, and firmware, up-to-date with the latest security patches to mitigate known RCI vulnerabilities. Fortigate periodically releases firmware updates that address security vulnerabilities, so it's crucial to apply these updates promptly.
Implement strict input validation and sanitization mechanisms in web applications and network services to prevent malicious command injection. Filter and validate user input to ensure that only expected and safe characters are accepted.

Keep all software, including operating systems, applications, and libraries, up-to-date with the latest security patches to mitigate known buffer overflow vulnerabilities. Fortigate periodically releases firmware updates that address security vulnerabilities, so it's crucial to apply these updates promptly.
Configure IPS policies on Fortigate to detect and block buffer overflow attacks. IPS can analyze network traffic for patterns indicative of buffer overflow exploits and block malicious traffic in real-time.
Use compiler-based or runtime-based stack protection mechanisms, such as stack canaries or Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR), to detect and prevent buffer overflow attacks at runtime.
